\begin_layout Standard
For both KNN and SVM we applied a centered log-ratio transform (CLR),
 standardized the CLR coordinates,
 then applied PCA.
 For KNN we used inverse distance weighting and tuned the PCA components and number of neighbors.
 For SVM,
 we used an RBF kernel and tuned the PCA components and penalty parameter 
\emph on
C
\emph default
.
 The kernel width parameter 
\emph on
gamma
\emph default
 was left at scikit-learn's default (
\family typewriter
scale
\family default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For random forest,
 we used the same CLR and standardization but omitted PCA.
 We tuned the number of trees,
 maximum tree depth,
 and minimum samples per leaf.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After selecting hyperparameters using area under the receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve (AUC) by grid search on the validation split,
 we fit each final pipeline on the training split.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cluster Abundance Profiles for Tetramer Counts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Run-level tetramer features summarize each sample with a single aggregate profile and do not capture how different sequence types are distributed within a run.
 To preserve this within-run compositional structure,
 we use unsupervised clustering followed by cluster abundance profiles (UC/CAP),
 a reference-free and alignment-free approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the sequence-level table is large,
 we first fit the unsupervised clustering model using only sequences from training-split runs,
 drawing at most a fixed number of sequences per run.
 For each selected sequence we computed a 256-dimensional tetramer composition vector,
 then fit 
\emph on
k
\emph default
-means to all selected sequences to obtain 
\emph on
K
\emph default
 centroids defining a sequence codebook.
 Dimensionality reduction with PCA before 
\emph on
k
\emph default
-means was trialed and found to degrade downstream classification results,
 so it was not used here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct run-level features,
 we applied the same centroid assignments (without refitting) to a larger per-run sequence budget for every run in the sequence-level table,
 including validation,
 test,
 and holdout runs.
 We counted cluster memberships within each run and normalized by the number of assigned sequences to produce a 
\emph on
K
\emph default
-dimensional cluster abundance profile (CAP).
 These CAP vectors serve as the feature matrix for supervised classification on both binary tasks,
 with downstream classifiers selected separately per task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
HyenaDNA and SetBERT Fine-Tuning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We initialized HyenaDNA from the 
\emph on
hyenadna-small-32k-seqlen
\emph default
 pre-trained checkpoint and fine-tuned one model per task.
 Binary cross-entropy loss was computed per task;
 because each run produces multiple sequence sets,
 training loss was averaged across all valid sets for a run.
 At evaluation,
 set-level logits were averaged to obtain one prediction per run.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For SetBERT,
 we used the released 
\emph on
qiita-16s
\emph default
 checkpoint:
 a 12-layer DNABERT encoder embeds each amplicon read into a 768-dimensional vector,
 and a 6-layer SAB transformer with 12 heads contextualizes the set of read embeddings,
 producing a [CLS] token embedding that summarizes the run.
 For each task we attached a classification head to the [CLS] token and trained with binary cross-entropy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although HyenaDNA offers larger context lengths (up to 1 million bases) and SetBERT was pre-trained with 1000 sequences per run and tested with up to 10,000 sequences per run 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LGA+25"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 we use a smaller number of sequences due to lower GPU resources (16 GB GPU RAM) available in our study.
 For HyenaDNA we packed non-truncated sequences from each run into the context window (up to 16k positions in our experiments) and generated 5 sets of packed sequences per run,
 representing up to ca.
 323 sequences per run.
 For SetBERT,
 we trimmed sequences to 150 bp (following the SetBERT paper) then used 350 sequences per run.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For both models we used a learning rate of 1Ã—10
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
âˆ’4
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the classification head and 1Ã—10
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
âˆ’5
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the backbone (a 10Ã— reduction to preserve pre-trained representations).
 Models were trained for 5 epochs.
 AUC was computed on the same splits used for the classical pipelines and the epoch with the highest validation AUC was selected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark dataset is composed of CSV files with instructions and scripts for downloading data from NCBI and preprocessing.
 The project code is written in Python with YAML configuration and a Makefile-driven analysis pipeline.
 The official HyenaDNA and SetBERT implementations were modified for this project and structured as pip-installable packages for import by analysis scripts.
 After downloading the data,
 the entire pipeline runs in ca.
 20 hours on a machine with 8 CPU cores,
 40 GB of RAM,
 and a 16 GB NVIDIA GPU.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define two binary classification tasks:
 
\series bold
cancer diagnosis
\series default
 (cancer vs.
 healthy,
 all samples) and 
\series bold
cancer type
\series default
 (breast vs.
 colorectal,
 cancer-positive samples only).
 Performance is reported as AUC on the test split (unseen samples from the development studies used to train the model) and the holdout split (entirely unseen studies).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For cancer type,
 all development studies for breast cancer are separate from all development studies for colorectal cancer.
 A model can therefore exploit study-level signals,
 e.g.
 different sequencing protocols,
 primer sets,
 or regional microbiome composition,
 as a near-perfect shortcut for in-study test performance.
 Holdout performance,
 where the model encounters new studies it has not seen during training,
 removes this shortcut.
 We accordingly expect cancer type to be the 
\emph on
easier
\emph default
 task for in-study test data but the 
\emph on
harder
\emph default
 task for holdout data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For cancer diagnosis,
 each included study contains both cancer-positive and healthy samples,
 so study identity alone does not predict the label.
 Models must learn biological differences between cancer and healthy microbiomes within studies,
 and those differences are expected to transfer,
 at least partially,
 to new studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classification with Run-Level Tetramer Frequencies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All models exceed the majority-class baseline on the test split,
 with particularly large margins for cancer type prediction (Table
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:tetramer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

).
 The holdout picture is sharply different.
 For cancer diagnosis,
 SVM achieves a modest AUC of 0.59 while random forest and KNN fall closer to baseline.
 For cancer type,
 SVM reaches an AUC of 0.71 while KNN collapses below baseline on holdout.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
