\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results are consistently lower on holdout splits than on in-study test splits.
 For run-level tetramer frequencies,
 the stark contrast betwen test and holdout performance (AUC >0.9 for test vs 0.71 or less for holdout) indicates that classifiers overfit to study-level signals when trained on single-study cancer-type data.
 Fitting to cluster abundance profiles (UC/CAP) preserves within-run compositional information and improves holdout performance on cancer type but not on the cancer diagnosis task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We list our per-study AUC for cancer diagnosis and comparisons with colorectal cancer where available (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:auc_comparison"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

).
 On two of the three development studies with a published comparison 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZTV+14,YDS+21"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 our test AUC is relatively high (0.98â€“1.00),
 but it drops to 0.73 on a third dataset where the literature value is 0.85 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BRRS16"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For holdout studies with published AUC values 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BWY+23,CAB+24,GYX+25"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 our AUC (0.66â€“0.68) is consistently lower than the literature (0.86â€“0.88).
 The literature numbers come from within-study cross-validation or test splits rather than independent cohorts and are therefore not directly comparable to true holdout performance.
\end_layout

